spanGrp.span: even if I ask you, you must not talk, even if I ask you
nake ng katyuuin a, a u si ku a xoa, [a] nake ng katyuuin a,
al vra ek jou, jy moenie praat nie, al vra ek jou
transcribed by ER in September 2008; last modified 02.02.2009; more or less OK, revised bz WI in Feb 2013 for DoBeS corpus project
/na/ (or /na ke/?): E says this means 'al' (dt.: 'ich frage euch schon'?!'); E has also used an explained it like this somewhere else; check!
check if /ka tyuuin/ always appears with the /ka/ particle => yes, it does!
E speaks to someone who sits next to her
E speaks to someone who sits next to her
you must not speak, I ? ask you
a u si xoa, nake katyuuin a,
jy moenie praat nie, al vra ek jou
E speaks to someone who sits next to her
once, a farmhand worked for the Boer
uin a ko ke, [huunsi] qhore xa siinsnn huunsi
ander dag het [die Boer] die hotnot by die Boer gewerk
E translates OBL either as 'by die Boer' or as 'vir die Boer'

"hotnot", is normally considered to be a racist term for coloured people in general, or for coloured or black people who work as servants on farms; but E does not know this negative connotation; for her, "hotnot", is the "normal", term for a servant, or "boy", who works on a farm

/ke/ sounds like [xe], but E says it is /ke/!; the /ke/ does not seem to be obligatory here, but it seems to belong to /uin a ko/; check again, but I think /ke/ is alright here (E also repeats [ke]), and says /xe/ or /xae/ is wrong!, but she translates it as 'het', but then she also goes on with ku xae ku, what is not said in the next rec.!)
he (the Boer) says to the farmhand
I will just say (= call him) Jakob, (because) I don't know his name
ng si maar ku Jakob, ng u xaea ku een,
ek sal maar s Jakob, (want) ek ken nie sy naam nie

Si and ER can't hear a /ka/ before /een/, but E says it must be there (E says ... xaea ka een (know the name) would be possible, but /*...xaea ku een/ is ungrammatical); /ka een/ seems to have an obligatory /ka/ prefix, even though it is hardly (or not at all) heard here (I have the same with F's /ka noqno/ 'shadow' in Janniejannie)
E talks to the people that are listening
you must go to, you must go to ...
a si ae, [a si] a si ae, ng ng]
E confirms that there is no OBL marker after ae, the [ngngng] is just stuttered
go and give him this letter",
a ng aa aaa kua xanisi a",
loop gee vir hom hierdie brief",

E says the beginning and the middle is stuttered, it should beginn with /ann aa/; if the beginning is not 2SG, then there should be an -a IMP suffix somewhere; /-a/ suffix on /aa/ was not repeated by E, but I can here something there; but might also be stuttered only?!
ng ng ng huun] ng huunsi,
E says /huunsi/ is the 'Boer', and /huunke/ is 'baas'; I am not convinced, and she should rather have said /ng huunke/ here (cf. next rec.)
E says /huunsi/ is the 'Boer', and /huunke/ is 'baas'; I am not convinced; the others have a different word for 'baas'
in repetition, /huunke/ somtimes sounds like [huunuke]; I have the same sometimes with /gunn-ke/ 'things' => [gunnuke]
(...) sounds more like /au ai .../; but E says it is /ku/; check again!
then you just sleep there (at baas Andries' farm)"
dan kan jy maar daar slaap",
alternative translation from E: 'dan moet jy maar daar slaap'
nice Imperative-construction; it should be OK like this; but check again, there was some variation when E repeated this
there he goes, (he) takes the letter, there he goes, (he) walks
anna ku, ai xanisi, ku anna, ku dyaqnn,
daar gaan hy, vat (hy) die brief, daar gaan hy, (hy) stap
he still walks, he still goes to that farm, (when) the sun goes down
[ku nog] ku nog dyaqnn, ku nog aa tya khaa, uin ee,
hy loop nog, hy gaan nog na daardie plaas toe, toe gaan die son onder
but he just walks, walks, walks
maar ku maar dyaqnn, dyaqnn, dyaqnn,
maar hy loop maar nog, loop, loop
toe kom hy mos daar na ...

first time that I hear /aa/ used as 'arrive at'; Geelmeidism?!; ? after a long discussion, E decided that he has probably arrived at the farm and is now maybe at the gate (what is context only, and not said explictly), and then he goes (from the gate etc.) to the Boer's house; check!
but the sun has already set
maar die son het al ondergegaan
alternatively repeated by E as: /nou uin ke al eea/ = 'nou die son is al (klaar) onder/die son het al onder gegaan'; the whole record sounds somehow different, but E seems to be quite sure about it
[ng ...] ng huunsi ke xa aea ng
sounds like [xanisi gee/ke] - [xanisi gee a] => [gee] might be the same as /dyee/; Sven hears [gyee]
check; 'is the 'verb' the same as in the preceding record?? /xanisi dyee a/? or is it /xanisi ke a/? might be the first one, since E's /ke/ often sounds more like [tye]
he gives the letter to the Boer
hy gee die Boer die brief
E says it is /huunsi ai xanisi/; the beginning seems to be stuttered; E is quite sure about it, so this is probably wat she wanted to say
he says "Jakob, do you (want to) go back again?"
hy s "Jakob, wil jy weer omdraai?"
first translation from E: 'Jakob, wil jy weer omdraai'; alternative: "Jakob, gaan jy weer terug?"
very nice: Baas Andries has the /ha/ pronoun, while Jakob is /ku/! it is similar as in Janniejannie, where different pronouns are used for different discourse participants
my master said I (should) just sleep (here)
huunsi ke xa kua, ng maar unn,
my baas het ges ek kan maar slaap
but I see, I see I still can walk, I (can) ...
maar nai, nai, si nog maar dyaqnn, ng
maar ek sien, ek sien ek kan maar nog loop,gaan, ek (kan) ...
E says [ae nng] and [aa nng] would both be OK
/ae nng/ might be a loan translation from Afrikaans; there is also a word /aru/ that means 'go home'
"nee baas, ek gaan maar huis toe",
E also repeats /ng si maar ae nng/; the /si/ is not here; /aa/ und /ae/ seem to be interchangable again!
the Boer says "yes, then walk now!
die Boer s "ja, nou loop maar!
(he) greets the Boer, there he walks
nebeke huunsi, ng anna ku dyaqnn,
(hy) groet die Boer, daar loop hy
E says there is no OBL marker here, the two [ng] probably phonetically again
[gaa ke a gaa ke al e,
E says she stutters a bit
what is the al-e / e at the end?
he walks, he walks, he walks, he walks, he walks
ku dyaqnn, ku dyaqnn, ku dyaqnn, ku dyaqnn, ku dyaqnn,
toe loop hy, loop hy, loop hy, loop hy
check English translation; (etwa: "wie der Teufel es so will ...?)
he makes that you get thirsty
ha [kxuu] kxuu, [na] na a khinn uin,
hy maak lat jy dors word
suddenly, he is nou thirsty, he ...
hy is nou skierlik dors, hy ...
he walks, again, then he comes (and) he sees
ku goe dyaqnn, ku saa, ku nai,
toe kom loop hy weer, toe sien hy

this is the exact translation given by E: "toe kom loop hy weer, toe sien hy",; what is the /saa/ 'come' here? does it really belong to /dyaqnn/, and why? alternative translation by E: 'hy kom loop aan en hy sien'
there is mos a fire, it shines there
ii ke mos naa, ha qaa ng ki naa,
daar is mos 'n vuur, hy lig daar
first translation by E: 'daar lig mos vuur'

E says you can't just say /naa/ at the end of the second part (instead of /ng ki naa/), but the /ng ki/ is obligatory before /naa/ here; it cannot be left out (/*ha qaa (ng) naa/ is ungrammatical acc. to E); what system is behind that?
ay, I am already thirsty, I just want to go there and ask for water
ai, [ng reeds] ng reeds khinn uin, tog aoa ng ng hoea khaa ng tyoxoe,
ai, ek is reeds dors, nou ek wil tog daar loop water vra
/nn/ or /ng/ is 'loop' here; E says it is not the same as /ann/; in the ditransitive elicitation most speakers gave /huiin - hoea/ etc. for 'ask for'
he walks, he walks, he walks, he ...
ku dyaqnn, ku dyaqnn, ku dyaqnn, ku
hy loop, hy loop, hy loop, hy ...
arrives, he sees that there is a farm
nae saa, ku naa, [khaa ke] khaa ke mos he a,
?was fr eine Struktur ist das denn? check again!
toe(t) hy kom toe sien hy maar is mos 'n plaas hierdie
the /e/ is almost always repeated by E; nevertheless, in one or two repetitions it was left out; what does it mean?? or is it /he a/?!
yes, there is a Boer's house, here it stands
ng, huunsi nng ke ha naaa,
I first had /naaa/ (did E repeat it like that?), but it is [naaa] only
(hy) loop na die Boer se huis toe
sound just like [uu aqe], but E says this is /aa ku aqe/; probably OK
toe sien (hy) 'n Boerevrou sit kama daar

E said first 'ou Boerevrou' for /huunsi orake/, but then she said just 'Boerevrou' is also OK; but it seems that the orake is reserved for elder people, and, as E said, this term cannot be used to refer to a 'meisie'
the /huun(si)/ is hardly to be heard, but there is "something", like [huun] there; I transcribe it, since /huunsi/ is heavily reduced by E on other occasions as well
sounds like [ha ka qann], but E rejects that there is a /ka/ present; she says it is stuttered again
nice: the 'old white woman' gets the /ha/ pronoun again (not /ku/); cf. also following records
nor sure if first /ha/ is really there
puts on (or: ?has put) on) her glasses, she sits and looks
gau hoo ha brilsi, ha kama soo, ha aqe,
sit haar brill op, sy kama sit en kyk
not sure if it is /hooa ha/, /hoo ha/ or just /hooa brilsi/; check tense and possessive pronoun again!
last version by E was /hoo ha brilsi/ 'sy sit haar bril op', at the beginning, it was 'sy het haar bril op'; this was also repeated on the next day (/hoo ha/ 'sy sit op')
check again; E did not really understand herself
/ou nooi/ ['missie, old mistress] is the female counterpart of /baas/
"ay, missie, I want a bit of water",
"ai, ou nooi, na aoa qhaa uni",
"ai, ou nooi, ek wil 'n bietjie water h",
E repeats as /huunsi orake naa ka/
"okay, I go and fetch water for you", when she speaks, fire ...
"okay, ng ang aa khaa", [naa] ha nae xoa, ii
okay, ek loop haal water vir jou", as sy praat, vuur ...
E repeats /okay, na .../, I hear /okay, ng .../; check again
nice: the witch has /ha/ as pronoun; the corresponding OBL for is here /naa/ (see next record)
ER: /aa/ here as the APPL form of /ai/?!
E says /aa/ is not the same as /(a)ng/; /nae/ seems to mean 'when, while' here; cf. also rec. 090; is this a regular pattern?
nice: the witch has /ha/ as pronoun; the corresponding OBL for is here /nng/ (see also preceding record!)
check if E repeats /ng naa/; actually, the /ng/ is not really audible
he sees, this is mos a ghost here
ku nai, hoqo ke mos he a,
toe sien hy, (dit) is mos 'n duiwel hier
on the first day, E translated /hoqo/ as 'duiwel', the next day as 'spook', and she said ''witch' would also be OK; I think 'ghost' is a better translation than 'devil' in English'
when the white woman goes to this side (= away, to fetch water)
huunsi oraki nae dyaqnn aa xaa a,
toe die ou wit vrou de kant toe loop ...
/nae/ seems to mean 'when, while' here; cf. also rec. 087
it seems as if /ku nau ae would be better/ (2009: why?)
hy harloop, daar die ou Boer vrou ...
[...] khai siia, [mos hoqo] a hoqo mos he
kom vinnig, sy is mos 'n duiwel, dis mos 'n duiwel
E repeats /saa/ instead of /sii/. I hear /sii, a/ or /siia/; E also once repeats /he/ instead of /e/; check!
check translationa dn structure again; the /a mos hoqo a/ might be "wrong", and E corrects herself to /a hoqo mos e/?!
"come take the water that you asked for",
"kom vat die water wat jou gevra het",
sounds different; check again, especially if /ai/ is really /ai/
the white woman says "take the water that you asked for
huunsi orake ka, "aia qhaa ha a hoea,
die ou nooi s "kom vat die water wat jy gevra het
check if the /a/ is supposed to be in again!
E says /ka/ and /ku/ is the same, both means 'say'
na amper aia ng [ga] ga broekusi se uutyuu",
ek vat amper aan jou broek se gat (= sterte)"
'vat aan' in translation corresponds nicely with OBL marker; is this again an Afrikaanism or Geelmeidism?
E repeats /ai-a/, but I do not hear an /-a/ suffix
E also repeats [broek-e-si], but it sounds more like [broek-u-si] here
hy hardloop maar hy take se rug out
das Wort hat irgendetwas mit Holkreuz machen beim laufen zu tun
he runs, he runs, he runs, he runs
ae, ku ae, ku ae, ku ae,
hy hardloop, hy hardloop, hy hardloop, hy hardloop
the white woman says "take the water that you asked for
huunsi orake ka, "aia qhaa ha hoea,
die ou nooi s "vat die water wat jou gevra het
I don't hear the /ha a/ here; sounds just like /ng/
na amper aia [ga] ga broekesi se uutyuu", huu,
ek vat amper an jou broek se gat",
huu, the thing (= Jakob) runs, the thing runs
(he) runs into the house (= his parents' house)
(toe) loop hardloop (hy) in die huis in
he goes and lies down, he dies (is unconsciuos)
E explains Jakob is not really dead, he is just "flou", ('weak; unconscious, insensible; dead-tired')
/tyoa/ = 'klaar wees', /tyoan'a/ = 'be absent'; not the same; checked with E; check also with other speakers
E says there is a /ha/ between the two words (/hoqo ha tyoana/); I don't hear anything
went back (or: turned around), or he disappeared from there
khaua, of ha uni ng tyoxoe,
is terug of hy is daar weg
stands up, "what is this, what is this?"
spring op, "wat is dit, wat is dit?"
E translates as 'opspring', but the verb just means 'stand up, get up'
ER: /aa tyaa/ 'l dood' means here 'he is unconscious' (SVC)
(they) struggle with him, struggle with him, (until) the sun comes out
[... ...] xana na ku, xana na ku, uin ng,
(hulle) sukkel met hom, sukkel met hom, toe die son uitkom
beginn is false start according to E
the sun goes along, it comes out, it goes along, it goes along, goes along
uin are, ha ng, ha are, ha are, are,
die son kom uit, en die son kom verby, en verby, en verby
sounds like [are] but in slow repetition with E it is [ere] = 'verbygaan'; Sands has /ere/, dic (347) has /are/;
E imitates here the stuttering of the scared Jakob
there seems to be no OBL!!! it is definitely NOT repeated by E, so the [ng] might just be 'stt...st..uttered'
E imitates here the stuttering of the scared Jakob
his father says "but you know there is no farm there",
ku ainki kua, "(...) mos xaea qhaa u naa tyoxoe,
sy pa s "jy weet mos daar is nie 'n plaas nie
(...): there is a click , but E repeats just /a mos xaea .../ 'jy weet mos'; it might probably just be stuttered again, but check!
the path (...) the Boer's farm, (...) not find another ?house
ann ke [neti mos] (...) huunsi qhaa (...) u nog hoo nng
die pad (...) die Boer se plaas, (...) kry nie nog 'n huis nie

E repeats /ann ke mos neti hoo ng huunsi khaa, nng ke u naa tya xoe??? hoo nng/; 'the path just comes from the Boer's [baas Andries'] farm, ???', die pad kom net van [baas Andries se] die Boer se plaas af, [maar] daar is nie [nog] 'n huis nie
B repeated /ku nou tyoa/, but there seems to be a click at the end; very softly spoken
he (Jakob) stands up, and now he sits down
ku maar khuung, ku nou suin,
toe staan hy maar op, en hy sit nou
(father) "but the Boer said, or did the Boer not say you (must) go and sleep (there)?"
"huunsi ke mos xa kua, of huunsi am xa kua, aa unn",
"die Boer het mos ges, of het die Boer nie ges nie, jy moet loop slaap?"
"die Boer het ges ek moet slaap
but I just thought I should just turn around",
maar xa maar ain, si maar khau",
maar ek het maar gedink ek moet maar omdraai",
/ain/ here without the /-ka/ suffix; why? because of past?; the click is missing, too; sound like /... maar ngkesi maar .../
